@flexiarg peeragogy/heartbeat
@title Keep a Visible Rhythm So the Group Has Something to Return To
@keywords rhythm, cadence, attention, energy, recurrence, individual-outreach
@audience peer-learning facilitators, group conveners
@tone practical
@style process-pattern
@references [peeragogy/wrapper peeragogy/carrying-capacity peeragogy/newcomer]

! conclusion: A peer-learning group needs a recurring, low-friction signal that calls attention back to the work — a heartbeat — without which energy dissipates and participants drift.  The signal can be impersonal (a weekly post, a shared rhythm) or personal (a direct message to someone who has gone quiet), but it must be frequent enough that absence is noticed and warm enough that re-entry is cheap.
  + context: Voluntary peer-learning projects compete with everything else in participants' lives.  Without a rhythm the group can return to, attention fades; the project drops out of mind individually before it dies collectively.  The heartbeat is the device that keeps the project resident in attention between bursts of activity.  It can be sustained by one person, by a role (see peeragogy/wrapper), or by an artefact like a wiki main page that someone tends.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: coordination overhead ↔ attention maintenance.
    Real: every heartbeat costs the heartbeat-keeper time and care; every missed heartbeat costs the group some fraction of its dispersed members.  Neither cost is zero.
    Irreducible: a group cannot simultaneously be self-organising and rely on no recurring signal.  Even fully decentralised groups end up with implicit heartbeats (a recurring meeting, a shared release cadence); the only choice is whether the heartbeat is named.
    Active: the pull recurs whenever the group is between visible deliverables, when a long-tenured member steps back, or when newcomers arrive expecting a shape they can attach to.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Personal nudge: someone (often the convener) writes individual notes to lurkers and dropped-out members, naming the work and offering a way back in.  High-cost per recipient; high return when the recipient was wavering.
    (2) Public cadence: a recurring artefact — weekly roundup, status post, agenda — that the group can read or skip without obligation.  Lower-cost per recipient; works when the artefact is reliably present.
    (3) Tended artefact: a shared surface (wiki main page, dashboard) that someone keeps current.  The heartbeat is the tending; the artefact is the trace.
    (4) Distributed rotation: the heartbeat-keeper role rotates so no single person bears the cost indefinitely.  Requires the role to be named explicitly enough that the next holder can take it over.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: the group has a recurrence that participants can name, and missing it is noticeable to more than one person.  Failing when: re-engagement happens only through one-off heroic effort by individuals, or when "what's happening with X?" is a question no one can answer cheaply.
  + ABSENCE-SIGNALS:
    - Silent drift: regular contributors stop posting and no one notices for weeks.
    - Re-onboarding burden: returning members ask the same orienting questions newcomers ask.
    - Convener fatigue: the project's continuity depends entirely on one person's ongoing attention with no redundancy.
    - Cadence collapse: a previously regular signal stops, and the group cannot tell whether the project is paused, finished, or dead.
